76561198045606366,Not Recommended,282050,17852016,"Posted: 2 September, 2015",all,Rock_It_Science,"Pros:+ Controls are responsive, and vehicle upgrades actually affect how your vehicle responds+ Has free ride mode (which is most of what I do in these games)+ AI is very balanced in difficulty, and can be very good+ You don't have to unlock tracks in free-play+ Can practice on any Supercross track in free-play mode+ The different sizes of vehicles have a clearly different feel (much more difference than reflex)Cons:- Only one (very small) free roam map, and there is currently no modding comunity for adding more- No cheats to unlock all bikes, so you will be grinding for a LONG time to unlock the 650's or the 50-pit bike- No rebinding controls other than 3 premade controller layouts (although keyboard layout is quite nice)- If you have multiple displays, the game will crash if you click outside of the game window, although alt-tabbing works fine- Still has quite a few crashes- haven't seen many updates since I've started playing the game- Only looks marginally better than other MX vs ATV games, and in some cases actually looks worse.- Menu's look much worse than Reflex (looks like they were from the PS2)- No trucks or UTV's!Other Notes:The new clutch system is very odd, and can get you going much faster than you could in other games, and get you into rhythems that would have otherwise been impossible to get into, but if you don't know about it, then racing will be very hard for you as the AI almost always use it.If there was one thing I would love the Dev's to add, it would be map support from other games in free-ride mode, or just more free-ride maps.Verdict:If you liked the Supercross modes from other MX vs ATV games, you'll like this game, because that is 90% of the game. If you were more like me and only ever played the free-ride from the other games (30+ hours of it on reflex on steam and 50+ hours on disc version of reflex) then you might want to pick up Reflex, 