76561197992661513,Recommended,282050,21662745,"Posted: 6 March, 2016",all,macbethloserkid,"UPDATE: In all fairness to Rainbow Studios, I promised to update this review if it changed. The game does seem to be running better now. The SX still drops occasionally, but it is nowhere near as bad as before and not too noticeable.I played one National event, and,  while not as smooth as I'd like, it is now playable and if you can deal with a few drops here and there, not bad. But also, having played the game more now, I do have a few complaints. Let's be honest, the DLC is a money grab here. Sell me the whole game up front. I get adding on new tracks as time goes by, but these were tracks released  on the original XBOX 360 and PS3 games, not brand spanking new. And having to pay for a bike that the competitor offers as standard is getting a little old. However, it is still a fun game. I bring up these issues in hopes that one day the developer will listen and I won't have to keep playing the lottery hoping I can win in order to fund the motocross game I'd like...you know, the tracks from the Lucas Oil Nationals and better physics. I mean, come on, I haven't played Budds Creek since Jeremy McGrath Supercross on the N64. GIVE THE PLAYERS WHAT THEY WANT, but I digress.If you like motocross/supercross, you'll like this game....hopefully they'll come out with a great sequel.ORIGINAL REVIEW:I have to say I regret purchashing this game a little. I read the other reviews and said, ""Maybe they're crazy and it runs just fine."" And then I bought it and said ""Nope, I am crazy for thinking it will be different."" I have an NVIDIA GTX 960 with the game installed on a SSD and the frame rate drops are so horrible on the Nationals tracks that I can't stand to play it. The drops aren't too bad on Supercross style tracks, but it is annoying. Having said that, maybe if I upgrade my old AMD A6 processor and added more RAM, it might run better as I've noticed memory and CPU to be very,very high while running this game. Also, dropping some of the settings seems to have improved it a bit. Other newer games run just fine, so maybe this one is just not optimized for PC.I will say that the handling does seem to be improved from the XBOX 360 version. My rider no longer does 360s on the ground a lot and doesn't seem to cross jump like a goon all the time. Is it the same as MX Simulator? No. But honestly, I haven't fallen over in real life as much as my MX Sim guy, so take it as you will.  Is it the same as MXGP? Not really. The turning still doesn't feel as nice. But, you can throw way better whips....in that you can actually control a whip. If you all ready own it on 360 or PS3, it's probably a waste of your time, but I am lazy and don't feel like walking to the other side of the house to turn on my 360, so I have it on here. It's just the same game though, there's not really anything new for you.If you like motocross, well supercross, then it's a decent game, assuming you have an extremely powerful machine, maybe. I don't know, that frame rate thing could be present on all of them. Or I guess you could just wait for the May release of the Xbox One version and stream it to your PC. But I cannot honestly recommend it until it can be played without frame drops on a modest PC instead of a ""Dude, I future-proofed the crap of my system"" PC. I'll update this review if anything changes."
